1449":"1449","Home, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Berwickshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Polwarth, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Polwarth, Berwickshire, Schotland","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Schotland"},"en":{"1330–Aft 1356":"1330–after 1356","1318–1385":"1318–1385","1330–1356":"1330–1356","1320–1377":"1320–1377","1350–1440":"1350–1440","1365–1449":"1365–1449","1295–1331":"1295–1331","1305–1365":"1305–1365","Aft 1356":"after 1356","1330":"1330","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1305":"1305","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","1365":"1365","1331":"1331","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","1449":"1449","Home, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Polwarth, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Polwarth, Berwickshire, Scotland","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hume","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Lowlands) and northern English: variant of   Hulme  , with loss of <i>l</i> before the bilabial consonant /m/, as in the vocabulary word <i>calm</i>. See   Holm   and   Home  .","Scottish: habitational name either from the barony of Home or from Hume (or Home) in Berwickshire, from which the barony took its name. The placename derives from Old English <i>hōum</i>, dative plural form of <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’.","History: A family of this name (see 2 above) have held the Earldom of Home since 1605."],"variants":[{"name":"Humes","meanings":["English (Durham): variant of   Hume  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>, or a variant of   Holmes  ."]},{"name":"Hulme","meanings":["English: variant of   Holm   and of   Home   3 and 4."]},{"name":"Home","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Hume  .","English: variant of   Holm  .","English: habitational name from Home in Clifton on Teme or in Feckenham (Worcestershire) or from a minor place similarly named, a variant of   Hamm   (from Middle English <i>ham(me)</i>, with rounding of the vowel before the nasal consonant to give <i>hom(me)</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Hume was born in 1330, in Midlothian, Scotland, her father, Sir Roger de Home - Fourth Laird of Home, was 35 and her mother, Christiana de Dunbar, was 25. She married Sir Patrick de Polwarth in 1355, in Polwarth, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died after 1356, in Polwarth, Berwickshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1330–Aft 1356":"1330–pärast 1356","1318–1385":"1318–1385","1330–1356":"1330–1356","1320–1377":"1320–1377","1350–1440":"1350–1440","1365–1449":"1365–1449","1295–1331":"1295–1331","1305–1365":"1305–1365","Aft 1356":"pärast 1356","1330":"1330","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1305":"1305","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","1365":"1365","1331":"1331","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","1449":"1449","Home, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Polwarth, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Polwarth, Berwickshire, Scotland","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scot